What you’re describing is Survivorship Bias.

The classic example (why this matters)

During WWII, analysts looked at returning planes and saw where they had bullet holes. The instinct was: reinforce those areas.

But mathematician Abraham Wald realized the opposite:

* The planes that made it back survived those hits
* The missing planes (the ones that got shot down) were likely hit in the areas with no holes on returning planes

So you reinforce the absence, not the visible damage.

